],
"forceOpen":true
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"e7d0bb",
"children":[
"Neutropenic patients and organ transplant recipients are at increased risk for developing ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Aspergillus"
]
},
" infections."
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_id_s17_2",
"title":{
"__html":"Testing"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"fa6a5a",
"children":[
"Testing"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"a2bad8",
"children":[
"Blood cultures are rarely positive. The initial test for suspected invasive aspergillosis is either serum galactomannan assay or, if negative, bronchoalveolar lavage with ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"polymerase chain reaction",
"children":[
"PCR"
]
},
" testing followed by tissue biopsy if necessary."
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_id_s17_3",
"title":{
"__html":"Treatment"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"4c4ac0",
"children":[
"Treatment"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"59b804",
"children":[
"Voriconazole is first-line treatment in patients with documented or suspected invasive aspergillosis. Surgical resection is indicated for aspergilloma and hemoptysis and is considered definitive therapy. Treat allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis with inhaled or oral glucocorticoids."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"2",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_id_f10"
],
"forceOpen":true
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"586d6a",
"children":[
"Patients with aspergilloma who are asymptomatic and have stable x-rays do not require therapy."
]
},
" "
]
}
]
}
]
},
